#Text=Pensacola
#Text=Pensacola is a historic beach city in northwest Florida , in the United States of America .
#Text=It is in Escambia County , Florida 's westernmost county , at the tip of the " panhandle " .
#Text=The city is home to the Pensacola Naval Air Station , the National Museum of Naval Aviation and many historic districts that skirt the downtown area .
#Text=Surrounded on three sides by water , the Pensacola area is full of history , shipwrecks , beaches and spectacular vistas .
#Text=Pensacola should not be confused with its neighbor , Pensacola Beach , covered in a separate article .
#Text=History
#Text=Pensacola has the nickname " The City of Five Flags . "
#Text=Only the Pensacola Chamber of Commerce actually uses that name , but it 's a convenient short-handed way of describing the city 's history .
#Text=Over the past 450 years , Pensacola has been owned by five nations : Spain , France , the United Kingdom , the United States , and the Confederate States .
#Text=It was also inhabited by various Native American tribes , but sloganeers never seem to include them .

#Text=When the Panzacola Indians arrived in Pensacola thousands of years ago , they found old growth pine forests , thicketed with massive pine trees so large , it would take two or three men to wrap your arms around the trunk .
#Text=These trees provided so much shade that there was almost no undergrowth on the forest floor , and traveling through the woods was easy .
#Text=Since there is n't much food to be found in pine forests , the tribes tended to live near the water , where fishing was plentiful .
#Text=Not much is known about these early inhabitants of the area :
#Text=they left few artifacts behind , and all of the tribes that lived in Pensacola prior to European colonization have gone extinct .

#Text=European colonization began with the Spanish : Juan Ponce de León ( of Fountain of Youth fame ) sighted the area first , and later Spanish explorers were excited by the well-protected , deep water bay .
#Text=They recommended settlement , and in 1559 , Tristán de Luna y Arellano arrived at the bay and founded the first European settlement in the United States .
#Text=He named it ... Puerto de Santa Maria .
#Text=It failed miserably .

#Text=He sent his men on worthless scouting missions into the desolate pine forests , lost all of his ships in a hurricane ( with the supplies still on board ! ) , and was so incapable and uninspiring that his men mutinied .
#Text=He lived , thanks to the intervention of Catholic missionaries in the town , but once Spanish ships arrived a few months later , the remaining Spaniards quickly abandoned the settlement .
#Text=Spain did n't return until 1698 .
#Text=They had rediscovered the bay five years earlier during a mapping expedition .
#Text=Since the bay was still a tempting harbor , and there were many old growth pines at the nearby Blackwater River that would be perfect for shipbuilding , Spain decided to resettle the bay .
#Text=This time , the settlement was named Bahía Santa María de Filipina .
#Text=Still not Pensacola !
#Text=However , the name ' Panzacola ' was written on explorer 's maps for the area , and the name was starting to gain informal use .
#Text=The settlement was poor , small , populated mostly by prisoners , and suffered many setbacks .
#Text=In 1719 , France , led by the governor of French Louisiana captured Pensacola from the Spanish at the outset of the War of the Quadruple Alliance .
#Text=There was almost no resistance from Pensacola : no one had bothered to tell the Pensacolians that they were at war !
#Text=The befuddled city greeted the French with open arms , expecting the ships from Mobile to trade supplies , not bullets .
#Text=After taking control , they did n't do much with the city .
#Text=The French burned Pensacola during their retreat in 1722 , and the Spanish resumed control of the ( pillaged , charred ) city ...
#Text=Until 1763 , when Great Britain won Florida from the Spanish as a concession following the French and Indian War/Seven Years ' War .
#Text=In exchange , Spain was allowed to keep Cuba , and was also given Louisiana as a gift from the French , in exchange for their help during the war .
#Text=Not a bad trade .
#Text=Great Britain was proud of its new city , and they put a lot of effort into improvement .
#Text=It was declared the capital of the new colony of British West Florida , and they built most of the streets in downtown Pensacola that are still used today .

#Text=This period of British prosperity did n't last too long though , because in 1781 , Spain recaptured Pensacola , along with the rest of Florida , as an ally of the United States in the American Revolutionary War .
#Text=Bernardo de Gálvez , the general of Spanish Louisiana , was instrumental in winning the city during the Battle of Pensacola .

#Text=When the Spanish fleet commander lost a ship and refused to send any more into Pensacola Bay , Gálvez used his powers as governor to commandeer one of the ships from Louisiana and personally sailed it into the harbor , under constant cannon fire from the British .
#Text=The other ships in the fleet soon followed , somewhat emasculated , one imagines .

#Text=With Florida now in Spanish control , Spain controlled all of the Gulf Coast , and parts of the Mississippi River , which resulted in a lot of discontent among United States settlers in the south .
#Text=They wanted water access , and their agitation for a seaport eventually inspire a young general named Andrew Jackson .
#Text=In 1821 , Jackson finally succeeded in capturing Pensacola , and Florida , for the fourth and final time : it was now owned by the United States of America .
#Text=The Adams-Onís Treaty made the acquisition official , giving Pensacola and all of Spanish Florida to the Americans .
#Text=This was a boon for Mississippi and Alabama , which finally gained access to the sea .
#Text=It was n't so great for General Jackson , who was made Governor of Florida , a job he hated , and later quit .
#Text=By this time , Pensacola had become the largest city in Florida , and was one of the most important ports on the Gulf Coast .
#Text=In 1845 the territory became the 27th United State .
#Text=The United States invested a lot in Florida , building forts here , increasing a military presence .
#Text=They built shipyards , which a hundred years later would become Naval Air Station ( NAS ) Pensacola .
#Text=In 1861 Florida seceded from the United States to join the Confederate States of America .
#Text=For four years , Florida fought with the South as part of the American Civil War .
#Text=Contrary to initial expectations , this war did not end well for the South .
#Text=Even worse for Pensacola , the Confederacy single-handedly destroyed the city 's economy .

#Text=Confederate Colonel John Beard , afraid that Union troops would capture Pensacola , ordered his men to " destroy every foot of lumber , all saw-mills , boats , etc. , " along with anything else that may be of use to " the enemy . "
#Text=The city 's economy never fully recovered .
#Text=Pensacola rejoined the United States in 1865 , beginning a long decline for the city .
#Text=The lumber industry began to rebuild , but by the 1930s , every old-growth tree in northwest Florida had been cut down , leaving nothing but small , newly planted pines .
#Text=Pensacola Bay , the entire reason for the city 's existence , was unable to accommodate modern ships , which required deeper water .
#Text=The city council declined to dredge the bay to make the water deeper , and the harbor declined to near nothingness .
#Text=Most of the shipping moved to Mobile , Alabama .
#Text=Today , the military is a driving force in Pensacola 's economy .
#Text=The Pensacola shipyards were re-purposed , and became the first naval air station in the United States in 1913 .
#Text=NAS Pensacola is home to the Blue Angels and the National Museum of Naval Aviation .
#Text=All naval aviators are , at some point in their career , trained at NAS Pensacola .
#Text=The base employs more than 23,000 people .
